"""
MKT Context Commentary — 2 Chronicles chapters 18–20
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-2chronicles-18-20.py

Ch18: Jehoshaphat joins Ahab at Ramoth-gilead
      ANE diplomatic alliance through marriage; prophetic consultation before
      battle (Mari parallels); court prophets vs. independent prophets; the divine
      heavenly council; "bread/water of affliction" as prisoner ration formula;
      royal disguise as ANE battle strategy; the random arrow as providential act
Ch19: Jehoshaphat's judicial reform
      Implementation of Deut 16:18 (judges in every gate); Mosaic judicial circuit;
      divine accountability of human judges; bicameral Jerusalem court (priest +
      civil ruler); corporate bloodguilt from corrupt verdicts
Ch20: Battle of Berachah — prayer, Levitical choir, miraculous victory
      Communal fast as crisis ritual (Joel 2; Ezra 8); Solomon's temple prayer
      fulfilled (2 Chr 6:24-25); Abraham as "friend of YHWH" (ʾōhēb); Levitical
      musicians as prophets (1 Chr 25:1-3); ark-before-the-army warfare typology;
      YHWH-as-ambush-setter; valley naming as memorial geography (Josh 8:2)

Key decisions:
- Ch18 divine council treated as genuine theological reality reflected in ANE
  cosmology, not merely literary device
- Ch19 judicial reform placed in context of Deut 16-17 without collapsing the
  distinction between Torah mandate and Chronicler's implementation account
- Ch20 Levitical choir before the army read against 1 Chr 25:1-3 prophetic-musician
  context, not merely liturgical performance
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRON2_CONTEXT = {
  "18": {
    "1": "<p>Jehoshaphat's great wealth and honor is immediately followed by his making a marriage alliance (<em>wayyi&scaron;taḥtēn</em>) with Ahab. Inter-dynastic marriage was the standard ANE mechanism for cementing political alliances: the Amarna letters (14th c. BC) document elaborate marriage negotiations between Egypt and Mesopotamian powers as the primary tool of international diplomacy. For Judah to ally with Israel through marriage represented a normalization of the post-division relationship &mdash; but from the Chronicler's standpoint, it entangled the Davidic dynasty with the apostate northern monarchy.</p>",
    "2": "<p>After some years Ahab invited Jehoshaphat down to Samaria and slaughtered sheep and oxen in abundance for him and the people with him, persuading him to go up against Ramoth-gilead. The elaborate feast before a military request was a well-established ANE diplomatic protocol: the banquet created social obligation and goodwill before the political ask was made. Ramoth-gilead was a strategically significant city east of the Jordan that Israel had long contested with Aram-Damascus; its capture would secure the northern Transjordanian trade routes.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&lsquo;As I am, so are you&rsquo; (<em>kāmôḵā kāmôḵā</em>) &mdash; the formula of equal alliance partners. This is the &lsquo;brotherhood of kings&rsquo; language documented in ANE international correspondence: equal-treaty relationships (as opposed to suzerain-vassal arrangements) used kinship vocabulary to define mutual obligation. Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s response commits Judah to full military participation in Israel&rsquo;s campaign, a commitment the subsequent narrative shows he should not have made.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s request to &lsquo;inquire first for the word of YHWH&rsquo; reflects the standard ancient practice of prophetic or omen consultation before military campaigns. The Mari texts (18th c. BC Syria) document prophets delivering divine messages about battle outcomes to the king; Assyrian and Babylonian records show liver divination, astrology, and dream interpretation serving this function throughout the ancient world. Israelite kings consulted YHWH through prophets rather than through divination, but the social function &mdash; divine authorization before battle &mdash; was universal in the region.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Ahab assembled 400 prophets. The large number (400) suggests professional court prophets whose livelihoods depended on royal patronage. The tension throughout chs. 18-20 between court prophets (who aligned with royal interests) and independent prophets (who aligned with YHWH&rsquo;s word) reflects a persistent social dynamic: the court employed professional religious specialists whose institutional survival depended on pleasing the king, while the independent prophetic tradition (Elijah, Micaiah, Amos, Jeremiah) maintained a separate, often confrontational relationship with the crown.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s request for &lsquo;another prophet of YHWH&rsquo; signals his awareness of the court-prophet/independent-prophet distinction. He recognizes that 400 prophets speaking in unison carries less evidential weight than one prophet with a reputation for independence. This was not ignorance of how prophecy worked; it was a reasonably sophisticated reading of the social dynamics of religious institutions.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Ahab&rsquo;s admission that Micaiah &lsquo;never prophesies good for me&rsquo; is a remarkable concession: the king knows this prophet speaks independently of royal preference, and he resents it. The Chronicler&rsquo;s point is that Ahab already knew what Micaiah would say &mdash; the consultation was performed for Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s benefit, not because Ahab wanted the truth. The bureaucratic official sent to summon Micaiah tries to coach him to align with the consensus, illustrating how institutional pressure operated on prophetic figures.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The summons of Micaiah by an officer shows that even independent prophets were accessible to the royal court through administrative channels. Micaiah was not an outlaw or refugee prophet &mdash; he was known and locatable. The prophetic office, even in its independent form, operated within the social fabric of the kingdom, not entirely outside it.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The kings were sitting on their thrones at the threshing floor (<em>gōren</em>) at the entrance of the gate of Samaria. Gates were the primary civic and judicial spaces of ancient Israelite cities: the space where elders sat, legal cases were heard, commerce transacted, and official assemblies held (Ruth 4:1-12; Amos 5:12; Deut 22:15). The threshing floor at the gate entrance provided an open flat area for large gatherings. The theatrical setting &mdash; two kings enthroned in full regalia watching 400 prophets perform &mdash; frames what follows as a public spectacle of prophetic power.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Zedekiah made iron horns as a prophetic sign-act. Enacted prophecy (symbolic actions accompanying or replacing spoken oracles) appears throughout the prophetic tradition: Isaiah walked naked for three years (Isa 20:2-3), Jeremiah wore and broke a yoke (Jer 27-28), Ezekiel acted out the siege of Jerusalem (Ezek 4). In the ancient world, the symbolic action was understood to initiate or guarantee the described event, not merely illustrate it. Zedekiah&rsquo;s iron horns claimed to embody Ahab&rsquo;s military power over Aram. The confrontation with Micaiah in v23 directly disputes the legitimacy of this sign.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The four hundred prophets prophesied in unison: &lsquo;Go up to Ramoth-gilead and succeed; YHWH will give it into the king&rsquo;s hand.&rsquo; The consensus of many prophets was typically understood as stronger evidence of divine will than the word of one; the social validation of large numbers was a real factor in how prophetic claims were evaluated. Micaiah&rsquo;s solitary dissent against 400 would have appeared, by ordinary standards of prophetic verification, as highly suspect.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The messenger who summons Micaiah urges him to agree with the consensus. This is not merely sycophancy; in ANE prophetic culture, consensus among multiple prophets was a legitimate indicator of divine will. The messenger&rsquo;s advice reflected a real hermeneutical principle: prophetic unanimity was taken as evidence of truth. Micaiah&rsquo;s refusal to conform is therefore not merely personal courage &mdash; it is a claim about the nature of prophetic authority that cuts against normal validation criteria.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Micaiah&rsquo;s initial response (&lsquo;Go up and succeed; YHWH will give it into the king&rsquo;s hand&rsquo;) is usually read as sarcastic mimicry of the 400, designed to provoke the king into demanding the truth. In ANE oracular culture, a prophet asked under pressure to speak the divine word was placed in a social bind: agree and compromise the oracle, or dissent and face consequences. Micaiah&rsquo;s ironic compliance forces Ahab to explicitly request a truthful word, shifting the moral burden back to the king.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Ahab adjures Micaiah to speak nothing but truth in YHWH&rsquo;s name &mdash; the formal oath formula used to compel truthful prophetic speech. Once the formal oath is invoked, Micaiah can deliver the true oracle. The adjuration structure demonstrates that prophetic speech operated within a legal-religious framework where sworn testimony had binding force.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Micaiah&rsquo;s vision of Israel scattered on the hills like sheep without a shepherd echoes a common ANE idiom for a leaderless, defeated people. The shepherd-king metaphor was ubiquitous in ancient Near Eastern royal ideology: kings were described as shepherds of their people in Mesopotamian, Egyptian, and Israelite sources. &lsquo;Each man to his house in peace&rsquo; is the dismissal formula that signals the army&rsquo;s dispersion after the king (the shepherd) falls.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The specific oracle (&lsquo;I saw all Israel scattered on the mountains as sheep without a shepherd&rsquo;) anticipates Ahab&rsquo;s death. The pastoral metaphor (sheep / shepherd) was deeply embedded in royal ideology throughout the ancient Near East: Mesopotamian kings bore the title &lsquo;good shepherd of the black-headed people.&rsquo; In Israelite usage, YHWH is the primary shepherd (Ps 23; Isa 40:11; Ezek 34), with the king as under-shepherd. The absence of a shepherd signals the king&rsquo;s death, not merely political chaos.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Ahab&rsquo;s complaint to Jehoshaphat (&lsquo;Did I not tell you he would not prophesy good concerning me?&rsquo;) reveals that the Ramoth-gilead consultation was a performance, not a sincere inquiry. The king who already knew the independent prophet would say &lsquo;no&rsquo; staged a consultation designed to produce a different answer for Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s benefit. The Chronicler&rsquo;s audience is expected to see through this.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Micaiah&rsquo;s heavenly court vision (&lsquo;I saw YHWH sitting on his throne, and all the host of heaven standing on his right and left&rsquo;) draws on the ANE concept of the divine council &mdash; the assembly of divine beings who serve the high god. Ugaritic texts describe El&rsquo;s assembly (<em>puhru</em> or <em>ʿēdat ʾil</em>); the Psalms reflect the Israelite version (Ps 82:1 &lsquo;God presides in the divine assembly&rsquo;; Ps 89:5-7; Job 1-2). In Israel&rsquo;s theology, YHWH presides over this assembly, and the spirit-beings serve as his council and messengers. The vision provides the backstage reality behind the prophetic consensus below.</p>",
    "19": "<p>YHWH asks &lsquo;Who will entice Ahab?&rsquo; &mdash; a deliberative question in the divine council. This form of divine deliberation appears also in Gen 1:26 (&lsquo;Let us make man&rsquo;) and Isa 6:8 (&lsquo;Whom shall I send?&rsquo;). The council model represents divine governance as participatory: heavenly beings propose courses of action, and YHWH authorizes or rejects them. The question is not YHWH&rsquo;s uncertainty but a narrative device for revealing the mechanism of how the prophetic consensus was produced.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Various spirits propose options and YHWH asks how. The council debate structure mirrors the judicial assembly format: multiple parties make proposals, the presiding authority decides. The purpose of the heavenly-council vision is to show that the 400 prophets&rsquo; consensus was not authentic prophetic inspiration but a deliberate divine permission for a lying spirit to operate through them &mdash; an extremely difficult theological statement about divine sovereignty and prophetic deception.</p>",
    "21": "<p>A spirit volunteers to be a lying spirit in the mouths of all the prophets. The concept of a <em>rûaḥ šeqer</em> (spirit of falsehood/lying spirit) authorized by YHWH to deceive is one of the most theologically challenging passages in the OT. It presupposes that YHWH can use deceptive means to accomplish judicial purposes: Ahab is already committed to a campaign that will kill him; the lying prophecy enables the outcome YHWH had already determined. Comparable ideas appear in 2 Thess 2:11 (God sending a &lsquo;strong delusion&rsquo;) and the hardening of Pharaoh in Exod.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&lsquo;YHWH has put a lying spirit in the mouth of your prophets&rsquo; &mdash; Micaiah makes the backstage reality explicit. This is not a claim that all prophetic utterance is suspect, but that the specific consensus of 400 in Ahab&rsquo;s court was divinely authorized deception for judicial purposes. The Chronicler presents Micaiah&rsquo;s disclosure as the most important act in the narrative: before the battle, the mechanism of the false prophecy is publicly revealed to both kings. Ahab proceeds anyway &mdash; which makes his death a matter of informed choice, not ignorance.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Zedekiah strikes Micaiah on the cheek. Striking the face was a profound insult in ancient culture signifying contempt and social invalidation (Job 16:10; Lam 3:30; Mic 5:1; Matt 26:67). The Piel verb <em>wăyyakkeh</em> (he struck) with the cheek as direct object is the technical form for an insulting slap. Zedekiah also delivers a theological counter-claim: &lsquo;Which way did the Spirit of YHWH pass from me to speak to you?&rsquo; This is the prophet&rsquo;s hardest question &mdash; how does one distinguish authentic from inauthentic prophetic inspiration? Micaiah&rsquo;s response is that events will verify.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&lsquo;You will see on that day when you go into an inner room to hide.&rsquo; Micaiah&rsquo;s counter-oracle to Zedekiah is predictive in the classic prophetic vindication formula: the truth of the oracle will be verified by what happens. The hiding in an inner room is the image of a frightened military survivor; Micaiah predicts that Zedekiah himself will be a refugee from the very battle whose positive outcome he proclaimed. The verification criterion &mdash; what actually happens &mdash; is the Deuteronomic test for true prophecy (Deut 18:21-22).</p>",
    "25": "<p>Micaiah is imprisoned and given &lsquo;reduced bread and water until I return safely.&rsquo; The &lsquo;bread of affliction and water of affliction&rsquo; (<em>leḥem laḥaṣ ûmayim laḥaṣ</em>) is a formulaic description of prisoner rations in Israelite idiom (also 1 Kgs 22:27; Isa 30:20). The phrase <em>laḥaṣ</em> (affliction, oppression) is the same word used for Israel&rsquo;s oppression in Egypt (Exod 3:9; Deut 26:7). Reducing a prophet to subsistence rations was a form of social and physical punishment designed to demonstrate royal power over the prophetic voice.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Ahab&rsquo;s instructions to put Micaiah in custody under the mayor of the city (<em>ʾāmer hāʿîr</em>) and the king&rsquo;s son indicate a formal administrative detention, not informal imprisonment. The involvement of both the city governor and the royal household in maintaining the prophet&rsquo;s custody reflects the bureaucratic seriousness of suppressing an unwelcome oracle. Micaiah&rsquo;s parting words &mdash; &lsquo;if you return at all in peace, YHWH has not spoken by me&rsquo; &mdash; is a classic prophetic self-verification challenge: the prophet stakes his credibility on the outcome.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&lsquo;Hear, all you peoples!&rsquo; &mdash; Micaiah&rsquo;s appeal to the gathered crowd as witness to his oracle. The call to witnesses is a formal legal procedure in ANE culture: witnesses validate the claim and can testify to its fulfillment. The public declaration before the assembled crowd transforms Micaiah&rsquo;s oracle into a testifiable claim with communal accountability. If Ahab returns, Micaiah is exposed as a false prophet; if Ahab falls, Micaiah is vindicated before the same witnesses.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The kings went up to Ramoth-gilead. Ahab&rsquo;s decision to proceed &mdash; knowing Micaiah&rsquo;s oracle, having been publicly warned &mdash; is the Chronicler&rsquo;s sharpest portrait of willful unbelief. The king who knew the verdict chose the campaign anyway. His disguise strategy (v29) is a tacit acknowledgment that he feared the prophetic word, even while refusing to heed it.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Ahab&rsquo;s disguise in battle was a military tactic to avoid being specifically targeted. In ANE warfare, killing the opposing king was the decisive victory: Assyrian reliefs show kings prominently identified by their clothing, regalia, and chariot position, making them high-value targets. Disguising as an ordinary soldier was a known countermeasure. Jehoshaphat, who kept his royal robes, thereby became the obvious target &mdash; a dangerous position that Ahab put him in through his own self-preservation strategy.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The king of Aram had commanded his chariot captains to fight only against the king of Israel. This order confirms the targeted-assassination strategy of ANE warfare: eliminate the opposing commander, and the army collapses. The Aramean commanders were searching specifically for Ahab&rsquo;s chariot position. When they mistook Jehoshaphat for Ahab and turned to attack him, Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s cry caused them to disengage &mdash; whether because they recognized his identity or because his cry was a signal they associated with the wrong king.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s cry to YHWH in the midst of the battle (&lsquo;YHWH helped him&rsquo;) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s unique addition to the parallel in 1 Kgs 22:32. The Chronicler consistently adds the theological explanatory note &mdash; divine help through prayer &mdash; that the Kings narrative omits. This is characteristic of the Chronicler&rsquo;s retelling strategy: filling in the divine causation that the earlier source left implicit.</p>",
    "32": "<p>When the chariot captains saw that Jehoshaphat was not the king of Israel, they turned back from pursuing him. The moment of recognition turned the tactical engagement. How the commanders recognized Jehoshaphat (royal attire? facial recognition? a spoken word?) is left unspecified. The Chronicler attributes the turning away to divine intervention; the Kings parallel mentions only that they turned away when they saw he was not Ahab.</p>",
    "33": "<p>&lsquo;A man drew his bow at random and struck the king of Israel.&rsquo; The <em>bĕtom</em> (innocently, randomly, without deliberate aim) is the key term: the arrow that killed Ahab was not aimed at him. The disguised king fell to an undirected arrow &mdash; the Chronicler&rsquo;s point being that Micaiah&rsquo;s oracle was fulfilled despite every human precaution Ahab took. The armor-joint gap was vulnerable by design (ancient armor had gaps at the joints of bronze plates for mobility); an arrow hitting that specific gap on an undirected shot is the providential fulfillment that renders Ahab&rsquo;s disguise futile.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Ahab propped himself in his chariot all day, facing Aram, and died at evening. The image of the mortally wounded king holding his position in the chariot until death is historically plausible as a command-and-control decision: if the king is seen leaving the field or collapsing, the army routes. His death &lsquo;at the going down of the sun&rsquo; ends both the battle day and the reign. The blood flowing from the wound into the chariot recalls Elijah&rsquo;s prophecy (1 Kgs 21:19) which was fulfilled when the chariot was washed at the pool of Samaria. The Chronicler does not add the dogs-licking-blood detail but the original audience would know the fuller story.</p>"
  },
  "19": {
    "1": "<p>Jehoshaphat returned safely to his house in Jerusalem. The Chronicler notes his survival without comment, letting the reader supply the contrast: the ally who prayed was preserved; the apostate host who disguised himself died. Safe return is the covenant-narrative marker of divine protection.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jehu son of Hanani went out to meet Jehoshaphat. Jehu&rsquo;s confrontation at the gate echoes a common prophetic pattern: the returning king is met at the city entrance by a prophetic spokesman who delivers a verdict on his conduct. Jehu had already rebuked Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s father, Asa, for his Aramean alliance (2 Chr 16:7 &mdash; the same Jehu, and both father and son made foreign alliances; the prophet&rsquo;s family has a history of confronting Davidic kings at their political compromise points). The rebuke uses the characteristic Chronicler formula: &lsquo;you have helped the wicked and loved those who hate YHWH; because of this wrath is upon you.&rsquo;</p>",
    "3": "<p>The prophetic rebuke is balanced by a recognition of genuine faithfulness: Jehoshaphat had removed the Asherah poles and had set his heart to seek God. The Chronicler&rsquo;s pattern throughout is nuanced: mixed kings receive mixed verdicts. The Asherah removal represents sincere cultic reform; the Ahab alliance represents political compromise. Both are real; neither cancels the other. The <em>dāraš</em> (seeking) vocabulary is the Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent marker of positive covenant orientation.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Jehoshaphat lived in Jerusalem, then went out again among the people from Beersheba to the hill country of Ephraim and brought them back to YHWH. The king&rsquo;s personal circuit of the people echoes the role of Moses in Deuteronomy: the covenant leader going among the people to reestablish the relationship with YHWH. The geographic span (Beersheba in the south to the hill country of Ephraim in the north) represents the maximum territorial reach of Judahite influence, including some former northern territories Jehoshaphat controlled.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Jehoshaphat appointed judges in all the fortified cities of Judah, city by city. The judicial reform implements Deut 16:18 almost verbatim: &lsquo;You shall appoint judges and officers in all your gates (<em>bĕkol-šĕʿāreḵā</em>) that YHWH your God is giving you, tribe by tribe.&rsquo; The fortified cities substituting for the Deuteronomic &lsquo;gates&rsquo; reflects the urbanized administrative reality of the monarchic period, where the gate-of-the-city and the city itself were effectively synonymous as administrative units. Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s reform is presented as Mosaic-Torah implementation, not political innovation.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&lsquo;Consider what you do, for you do not judge for man but for YHWH.&rsquo; This theological grounding of human jurisprudence is distinctive in the ancient world. Hammurabi&rsquo;s law code attributed its authority to Shamash, the sun-god of justice, but the judge administered the king&rsquo;s law, not directly the god&rsquo;s. Deuteronomy and Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s charge go further: the judge stands before YHWH himself, not merely under divine sanction for royal law. The accountability is direct and personal, not mediated through the king. &lsquo;He is with you in giving judgment&rsquo; &mdash; divine presence in the judicial process itself.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&lsquo;Now let the fear of YHWH be upon you. Be careful what you do, for there is no injustice with YHWH our God, or partiality, or taking bribes.&rsquo; The three prohibited judicial corruptions (injustice, partiality, bribery) recur throughout the Torah (Exod 23:2-8; Deut 16:19; Lev 19:15). The specific prohibition against partiality (<em>massēʾ pānîm</em>, lifting the face = showing favoritism) and bribery (<em>miqaḥ šōḥad</em>) addresses the two primary corruptions of ancient courts: ruling for the powerful and ruling for the wealthy. The appeal to YHWH&rsquo;s own character as the model for judicial conduct (&lsquo;there is no injustice with YHWH&rsquo;) grounds the ethical demand in the divine nature.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Jerusalem central court is appointed from Levites, priests, and heads of families. This tricameral composition &mdash; Levites, priests, and lay elders &mdash; matches the Mosaic model (Deut 17:8-12) where difficult cases were brought to the central sanctuary for adjudication by priests and judges. The Jerusalem court served the appellate function that Moses&rsquo; personal judiciary served in the wilderness (Exod 18:25-26; Deut 1:9-17). Amariah the chief priest handled religious questions; Zebadiah the leader of Judah handled civil matters &mdash; a functional separation of church and state in judicial administration that anticipates later distinctions.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&lsquo;Thus you shall do, in the fear of YHWH, faithfully and wholeheartedly.&rsquo; The twofold requirement &mdash; faithfulness (<em>beʾĕmûnāh</em>) and wholehearted devotion (<em>bĕlēḇāḇ šālēm</em>) &mdash; mirrors the Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent language for genuine covenant orientation. A partial heart (<em>lēḇāḇ ḥālûq</em>, divided heart) produces institutional religiosity without personal transformation; the whole heart produces judicial integrity because the judge&rsquo;s motivation is devotion to YHWH rather than self-interest.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&lsquo;Whatever case comes to you from your brothers who live in their cities &mdash; whether bloodshed or law or commandment, statutes, or rules &mdash; you shall warn them, so that they do not incur guilt before YHWH and wrath come upon you and your brothers.&rsquo; The warning requirement addresses the corporate dimension of judicial failure: bad verdicts implicate the entire community in bloodguilt (cf. Deut 21:1-9, the unsolved murder procedure designed to remove communal bloodguilt). Wrath (<em>qeṣep</em>) comes on the judges <em>and</em> their brothers &mdash; individual judicial corruption has communal consequences.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The division of jurisdictions &mdash; Amariah for religious matters, Zebadiah for civil matters &mdash; with the Levites as officials (<em>šōṭĕrîm</em>) completes the judicial structure. The <em>šōṭēr</em> (officer, official) role appears throughout Deuteronomy (Deut 1:15; 16:18; 20:5) as the administrative support of the judicial system &mdash; they enforced decisions and maintained order in the courts. The closing charge &lsquo;act courageously, and may YHWH be with the upright&rsquo; uses the same <em>ḥāzaq</em> (be strong, act courageously) vocabulary as the Davidic-Solomonic charge (1 Chr 22:13; 28:20), linking the judicial vocation to the same covenant-courage framework as the royal and military vocations.</p>"
  },
  "20": {
    "1": "<p>After this the Moabites, Ammonites, and some of the Meunites came against Jehoshaphat for battle. The three groups represent the Transjordanian and southern-desert peoples who periodically raided or invaded Judah from the east. The Meunites (<em>mĕʿûnîm</em>) were a people from the region south of the Dead Sea (cf. 2 Chr 26:7 where they appear again). Their coalition against Jehoshaphat immediately follows the Ramoth-gilead episode and Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s judicial reforms &mdash; the Chronicler&rsquo;s implicit pattern: reform → testing.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&lsquo;A great multitude is coming against you from Edom, from beyond the sea.&rsquo; The Dead Sea (&lsquo;the sea&rsquo;) divides Judah from Edom-Moab territory; the attack comes across or around the southern end of the Dead Sea, a route that would bring an invading army to En-gedi (a spring oasis on the western shore). The specific route &mdash; through wilderness, from the east &mdash; bypassed the normal northern approach and threatened Judah&rsquo;s vulnerable southeastern flank.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Jehoshaphat was afraid and set his face to seek YHWH and proclaimed a fast throughout all Judah. The communal fast as a response to military crisis was a standard Israelite ritual: Joel 2:12-17 prescribes fasting and assembly; Ezra 8:21-23 records a pre-journey fast; Neh 1:4 records individual fasting in crisis; Jonah 3:5-10 shows even Gentiles understanding the function. Fasting in the ancient world signified corporate acknowledgment of dependence, urgent petition, and willingness to forgo normal pleasures to focus communal attention on the crisis. The proclamation of a fast throughout all Judah made the prayer national.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Judah assembled to seek help from YHWH from all the cities of Judah they came to seek YHWH. The centralization of prayer at Jerusalem (the temple) was the specific function Solomon&rsquo;s dedication prayer anticipated: 2 Chr 6:24-25 contains a specific petition for exactly this situation: &lsquo;if your people Israel are defeated before the enemy because they have sinned against you... yet if they turn to you and acknowledge your name and pray and plead with you in this house, then hear from heaven and forgive the sin of your people Israel and bring them back to the land.&rsquo; Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s national assembly at the temple is the fulfillment of Solomon&rsquo;s prayer template.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Jehoshaphat stood in the assembly of Judah and Jerusalem, in the house of YHWH, before the new court. The &lsquo;new court&rsquo; (<em>heḥāṣēr heḥăḏāšāh</em>) is the outer court of the temple, possibly an expansion or renovation. The king&rsquo;s standing position before the congregation for corporate prayer matches Solomon&rsquo;s position in 2 Chr 6:12-13 (Solomon &lsquo;stood before the altar of YHWH in the presence of all the assembly of Israel and spread out his hands&rsquo;). The king as covenant mediator and chief intercessor &mdash; leading the people in prayer in the temple &mdash; is a distinctly Chronicler theme.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The prayer opens: &lsquo;O YHWH, God of our fathers, are you not God in heaven? You rule over all the kingdoms of the nations. In your hand are power and might, so that none is able to withstand you.&rsquo; The invocation follows the standard lament-psalm structure: address (YHWH, God of our fathers), attribute (&lsquo;God in heaven, ruler over nations&rsquo;), and incomparability claim (&lsquo;none can withstand you&rsquo;). The appeal to the &lsquo;God of our fathers&rsquo; grounds the petition in covenant history; the appeal to divine sovereignty over all nations reframes the Moab-Ammon coalition as less formidable than it appears.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&lsquo;Did you not, our God, drive out the inhabitants of this land before your people Israel, and give it forever to the descendants of Abraham your friend?&rsquo; The designation of Abraham as YHWH&rsquo;s <em>ʾōhēḇ</em> (one who loves, friend) appears in the OT only here and in Isa 41:8 (&lsquo;Abraham, my friend&rsquo;). This title for Abraham appears in later Jewish literature (Jubilees 19:9), is preserved in Arabic as <em>al-Khalīl</em> (the friend), and appears in James 2:23 (&lsquo;Abraham was called a friend of God&rsquo;). The prayer&rsquo;s appeal to Abrahamic friendship establishes the land-gift as a covenant obligation YHWH made to his most intimate human partner.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&lsquo;They lived in it and built for you in it a sanctuary for your name.&rsquo; The prayer traces the narrative from conquest to temple: land-gift → settlement → temple-building. The temple is the culmination of the Abrahamic land-gift narrative, making Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s prayer in the temple the proper locus for claiming the covenant promises. The historical recitation in a lament prayer serves to hold YHWH accountable to his own covenant commitments &mdash; a legitimate rhetorical strategy in biblical prayer that appears throughout the Psalms (Ps 44; 74; 79; 89).</p>",
    "9": "<p>&lsquo;If disaster comes upon us, the sword, judgment, pestilence, or famine, we will stand before this house and before you &mdash; for your name is in this house &mdash; and cry out to you in our affliction, and you will hear and save.&rsquo; This verse is a direct citation of Solomon&rsquo;s dedication prayer (2 Chr 6:28-30), where Solomon had prayed precisely for this: that YHWH would hear from heaven when his people faced sword, famine, and pestilence and cried out toward the temple. Jehoshaphat is not improvising; he is activating a prayer-template that was already built into the temple&rsquo;s founding.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The historical paradox at the center of the prayer: the Moabites and Ammonites are the very peoples whom Israel was not permitted to attack when they came from Egypt (Deut 2:9, 19 &mdash; YHWH explicitly commanded Israel not to harass Moab or Ammon or contend with them). Now those same protected peoples have come to attack Judah. The prayer exploits the irony: Israel honored YHWH&rsquo;s boundary-commands by not conquering these nations; those nations have now repaid that deference with invasion. The prayer asks YHWH to vindicate his own protection-command.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&lsquo;Behold, they reward us by coming to drive us out of your possession that you have given us to inherit.&rsquo; The land is defined as YHWH&rsquo;s possession (<em>yĕrûšāh</em>) given to Israel as inheritance (<em>naḥalāh</em>). The attack is framed not as a political problem but as a theological problem: attacking Israel is attacking YHWH&rsquo;s inheritance. The prayer leverages the theological stakes to move from a military crisis to a theological claim on divine protection.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&lsquo;O our God, will you not execute judgment on them? For we are powerless against this great horde that is coming against us. We do not know what to do, but our eyes are on you.&rsquo; The confession of powerlessness (<em>ʾên bānû kōaḥ</em>) and the fixing of eyes on YHWH is one of the OT&rsquo;s most direct expressions of covenant dependence. The prayer does not ask for a strategy or a miracle weapon; it asks for divine judgment because the community has nothing else. &lsquo;Our eyes are on you&rsquo; (<em>ʿênênû ʾēlêḵā</em>) is the posture of complete helplessness resolved into complete trust &mdash; the same posture described in Ps 123:1-2 and Ps 25:15.</p>",
    "13": "<p>All Judah stood before YHWH, with their little ones, their wives, and their children. The assembly includes the entire community: not just fighting men but families. The presence of women and children at the prayer assembly signals that this is a communal covenant event, not merely a military council. The whole-community fast and prayer creates the social solidarity of shared vulnerability that makes the subsequent deliverance a communal, not military, victory.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Spirit of YHWH came upon Jahaziel son of Zechariah, a Levite of the sons of Asaph, in the midst of the assembly. Asaph&rsquo;s sons were the Levitical singing guild established by David (1 Chr 25:1-3); the Chronicler specifically noted that they &lsquo;prophesied (<em>nāḇāʾ</em>) with lyres, with harps, and with cymbals.&rsquo; Jahaziel&rsquo;s Spirit-utterance in the assembly fulfills this dual identity of Asaphite musicians as prophets: the Levitical musician who prophesied in worship now prophesies the divine word into a military crisis. The Spirit coming on a Levite singer (not a court prophet or official priest) in the temple assembly is one of the Chronicler&rsquo;s distinctive portraits of how divine communication worked in the Second Temple ideal.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&lsquo;Listen, all Judah and inhabitants of Jerusalem and King Jehoshaphat: thus says YHWH to you.&rsquo; The prophetic messenger formula through a Levitical musician addressed first to the people, then the king, reverses the normal social order (king → people). The oracle form (&lsquo;thus says YHWH&rsquo;) signals authoritative divine speech. The content: &lsquo;Do not be afraid and do not be dismayed at this great horde, for the battle is not yours but God&rsquo;s.&rsquo; The &lsquo;battle belongs to YHWH&rsquo; formula echoes David&rsquo;s word to Goliath (1 Sam 17:47) and throughout the holy-war tradition, where YHWH fights for Israel while Israel observes.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The specific route is given: &lsquo;Tomorrow go down against them. Behold, they will come up by the ascent of Ziz. You will find them at the end of the valley, east of the wilderness of Jeruel.&rsquo; The geographical specificity (Ziz pass, valley east of the wilderness of Jeruel) corresponds to routes from the Dead Sea shore toward Tekoa. The provision of tactical information within a prophetic oracle signals that this is not merely encouragement but a genuine divine revelation of the enemy&rsquo;s position &mdash; intelligence that made Israel&rsquo;s preparation purposeful rather than desperate.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&lsquo;You will not need to fight in this battle. Stand firm, hold your position, and see the salvation of YHWH on your behalf, O Judah and Jerusalem.&rsquo; The command to stand and observe rather than fight is the extreme form of holy-war instruction: Israel&rsquo;s military contribution is positional (stand your ground) while YHWH executes the actual combat. The closest parallel is Exod 14:13-14 where Moses tells Israel at the Red Sea: &lsquo;YHWH will fight for you, and you have only to be silent.&rsquo; The non-combat victory is the Chronicler&rsquo;s most direct expression of covenant warfare theology.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Jehoshaphat bowed his face to the ground, and all Judah and the inhabitants of Jerusalem fell down before YHWH, worshipping YHWH. The corporate prostration (bow + fall + worship) is the formal assembly response to a received prophetic oracle: the community acknowledges the divine word by physical submission before speaking it has been verified. The response also establishes the communal context of what follows: the singing, the marching, the ambush victory are all extensions of the worship that began here.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The Levites from the Kohathites and the Korahites stood up to praise YHWH God of Israel with a very loud voice. The Korahites are the singing guild (Ps 42-49; 84-85; 87-88 bear their names in the superscriptions); they join the Kohathites in loud praise as the corporate response to the prophetic oracle. The praise at the eve of battle is not a morale-booster; it is the continuation of the worship assembly that constitutes the community&rsquo;s relationship with YHWH as their divine warrior.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&lsquo;Believe in YHWH your God and you will be established; believe his prophets and you will succeed.&rsquo; The verse plays on the <em>ʾāman</em> root: <em>heʾāmînû</em> (trust/believe) in YHWH produces <em>tēʾāmēnû</em> (being established/made firm) &mdash; the same root that produces <em>ʾāmēn</em>. The wordplay creates a theological proposition: the community that trusts (<em>heʾāmîn</em>) in YHWH will itself become firm (<em>ʾāman</em>). This is not mere word-play; it embeds covenant ontology &mdash; the trusting community acquires the quality it trusts in.</p>",
    "21": "<p>After consulting with the people, Jehoshaphat appointed those who were to sing to YHWH and praise him in holy attire (<em>bĕhaḏrat qōḏeš</em>) as they went before the army. The placement of the Levitical choir before the army inverts the normal battle order. In the wilderness, the ark of the covenant went before the army (Num 10:33-36); here the singers replace the ark in that forward position. The Jericho march (Josh 6) provides a closer parallel: the priests and the ark led the march, and the military followed. Sending singers &lsquo;into the wilderness&rsquo; before the warriors is an unprecedented act of covenant vulnerability that made military sense only within the holy-war framework.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&lsquo;And when they began to sing and praise, YHWH set an ambush (<em>ʾōrĕḇîm</em>) against the men of Ammon, Moab, and Mount Seir.&rsquo; The divine ambush at the moment of worship is the Chronicler&rsquo;s most dramatic expression of the worship-warfare connection. <em>ʾāraḇ</em> (to lie in ambush) is the standard military term for the Israelite ambush strategy at Ai (Josh 8:2, 7, 9). YHWH himself performing the ambush at the moment the choir began is the complete inversion of human military strategy: Israel&rsquo;s contribution was song; YHWH&rsquo;s contribution was the tactical ambush.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The Ammonites and Moabites rose against the inhabitants of Mount Seir, destroying them utterly, and when they had finished the men of Seir, they helped destroy each other. The coalition turned on itself &mdash; a pattern found in several OT battle narratives (Judg 7:22 at Gideon&rsquo;s battle; 1 Sam 14:20 at Jonathan&rsquo;s Philistine rout). ANE coalition warfare was inherently fragile: allies with different objectives and mutual territorial interests were prone to conflict over spoils or strategic disagreement. The Chronicler attributes this self-destruction to divine action, but the social dynamics of unstable coalitions provide the mechanism.</p>",
    "24": "<p>When Judah came to the watchtower of the wilderness, they looked toward the horde, and behold, there were dead bodies on the ground; none had escaped. The scouting position (watchtower, <em>miṣpeh</em>) at the edge of the wilderness was a high vantage point from which to observe the valley below. What they saw was the aftermath of the coalition&rsquo;s self-destruction: a scene of complete devastation without any Judahite military engagement. The visual discovery of a won battle matches the oracle exactly: &lsquo;you will not need to fight.&rsquo;</p>",
    "25": "<p>The people of Judah and Jerusalem came and took the spoil &mdash; more than they could carry. <em>rĕkûš</em> (possessions, property), <em>pĕgārîm</em> (corpses, possibly used here for equipment left on the dead), clothing, and valuable things. The plundering took three days because there was so much. The three-day plunder echoes the three-day festival after crossing the Jordan (Josh 3:2) and the three-day rest festivals throughout the wilderness narrative; it marks the completeness of the victory.</p>",
    "26": "<p>On the fourth day they assembled in the Valley of Berachah, for there they blessed YHWH. Therefore the name of that place has been called the Valley of Berachah to this day. The naming of a valley after a specific divine act is the standard etiological pattern throughout Joshua and Judges: place-names encode theological memory. <em>bĕrāḵāh</em> (blessing) creates the Valley of Blessing as a geographic monument to the prayer-and-praise strategy that produced the victory. Memorial geography is how covenant victories were transmitted across generations.</p>",
    "27": "<p>They returned to Jerusalem with joy, for YHWH had made them rejoice over their enemies. <em>śimḥāh</em> (joy) as the characteristic response to divine deliverance appears throughout the Psalms (Ps 30:11; 126:3) and throughout Chronicles as the emotional register of authentic worship (2 Chr 23:21; 24:10; 29:30; 30:23, 25-26). The return procession &mdash; with lyres, harps, and trumpets &mdash; to the house of YHWH is the conclusion of the liturgical arc that began with the assembly, fast, and prayer in ch. 20:3-13.</p>",
    "28": "<p>They came to Jerusalem with harps (<em>nĕḇālîm</em>), lyres (<em>kinnōrôt</em>), and trumpets (<em>ḥăṣōṣĕrôt</em>) to the house of YHWH. The three instruments correspond to the Levitical music service: the stringed instruments were the Levitical choir instruments; the trumpets were the priestly instruments (Num 10:1-10). The return to the temple with all three categories of sacred music completes the liturgical frame: the battle began in the temple with prayer and worship; it ends in the temple with the same.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The fear of God came upon all the kingdoms of the lands when they heard that YHWH had fought against the enemies of Israel. The divine reputation established by the non-combat victory extends to the surrounding nations &mdash; the same effect Solomon&rsquo;s wisdom and temple produced (2 Chr 9:1, 23). The <em>paḥad ʾĕlōhîm</em> (fear of God) falling on surrounding nations is the Deuteronomic international-reputation blessing (Deut 2:25; 11:25): obedience produces a divine terror that precedes Israel&rsquo;s advance. The peaceable outcome of Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s chapter is that the surrounding nations were quiet (<em>šāqaṭ</em>) before him.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The realm of Jehoshaphat was quiet (<em>tišqōṭ malkûtô</em>), for his God gave him rest on every side. <em>šāqaṭ</em> (to be quiet, undisturbed) is the Deuteronomic rest-vocabulary: the state of security when enemies are pacified (Judg 3:11; 5:31; 8:28; 2 Chr 14:5-6). The giving of rest on every side is the language of the Davidic promise (1 Chr 22:9) and the Solomonic fulfillment (2 Chr 14:7). Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s victory through prayer and praise brings him to the same covenant-rest condition as the golden-era kings.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The regnal summary begins: Jehoshaphat was thirty-five years old when he began to reign and reigned twenty-five years in Jerusalem. His mother was Azubah the daughter of Shilhi. The regnal data anchors the narrative in the standard Deuteronomistic framework of Chronicles: age, regnal length, mother&rsquo;s name, capital city. The mother&rsquo;s name (&lsquo;Azubah&rsquo; = abandoned) and her father Shilhi&rsquo;s name carry no further narrative significance here.</p>",
    "32": "<p>He walked in the way of his father Asa and did not turn aside from it, doing what was right in the sight of YHWH. The father-comparison is the standard positive Chronicler benchmark. The caveat that follows &mdash; the high places were not removed, the people had not yet set their hearts to the God of their fathers &mdash; represents the structural limitation of even the best reform kings: personal royal piety could not override ingrained popular syncretism. The Chronicler uses this pattern repeatedly (Asa, Jehoshaphat, Hezekiah) to show that reform kings were genuinely faithful but institutionally incomplete.</p>",
    "33": "<p>&lsquo;The high places were not taken away; the people had not yet set their hearts toward the God of their fathers.&rsquo; The incomplete reform is not attributed to Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s personal failure (unlike his foreign alliances) but to the spiritual inertia of the people. The phrase <em>hēkînû lĕḇāḇām</em> (established/prepared their heart) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s standard for wholehearted covenant loyalty (cf. 2 Chr 12:14 for Rehoboam&rsquo;s failure to establish his heart; 2 Chr 19:3 for the positive statement about Jehoshaphat). Popular religiosity lagged the royal reform.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The rest of the acts of Jehoshaphat, from first to last, are written in the chronicles of Jehu son of Hanani, which is recorded in the Book of the Kings of Israel. Jehu son of Hanani &mdash; the same prophet who rebuked Jehoshaphat at the start of ch. 19 &mdash; is cited as the primary historical source. The Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent citation of prophetic sources signals that history is interpreted, not merely recorded: the sources are themselves theological interpreters of the events they witnessed.</p>",
    "35": "<p>After this Jehoshaphat king of Judah joined with Ahaziah king of Israel in wickedness. The maritime alliance with Ahaziah (Ahab&rsquo;s apostate son who &lsquo;did very wickedly&rsquo;, 1 Kgs 22:52) provides the narrative close to a chapter defined by the contrast between trust-in-YHWH (prayer, choir, non-combat victory) and alliance-with-apostasy (commercial partnership with the northern apostate king). The second alliance mirrors the first (ch. 18): Jehoshaphat cannot resist the pull toward northern political partnership.</p>",
    "36": "<p>They made ships to go to Tarshish. The joint maritime venture at Ezion-geber on the Gulf of Aqaba echoed Solomon&rsquo;s Ophir trade (2 Chr 8:17-18; 9:21): the Red Sea port was the launching point for long-distance trade missions. The Solomon-and-Hiram precedent made it an attractive model; but Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s partner was Ahaziah (apostate), not Hiram (Tyrian craftsman with legitimate commercial relationship). Eliezer son of Dodavahu prophesied that YHWH would break the works because of the partnership.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Eliezer&rsquo;s prophecy was fulfilled: the ships were wrecked and were not able to go to Tarshish. The broken ships at Ezion-geber are a smaller-scale version of the prophetic-word-fulfilled pattern that governed ch. 18: Micaiah&rsquo;s oracle was fulfilled through a random arrow; Eliezer&rsquo;s oracle was fulfilled through shipwreck. In both cases, Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s alliance with an apostate northern king produced a prophetically-announced disaster. The chapter ends on a note of structural irony: the king who triumphed through prayer alone failed through commercial partnership.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    data = load_comm('mkt-context', '2chronicles')
    merge_comm(data, CHRON2_CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '2chronicles', data)
    total = sum(len(vs) for vs in CHRON2_CONTEXT.values())
    print(f'2chronicles mkt-context ch 18-20: wrote {total} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
